The portfolio weight of investment is computed as follows: 

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Porfolio weight}&=\dfrac{\text{Investment value}}{\text{Total portfolio value}}
\end{aligned}$$

Then, let us also determine Stock B's value by using the same formula from step 5. The Stock B's value is computed as follows: 

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Stock B's value}&={\text{\$19.00 $\times$ 180 shares }}\\
&={\textbf{\$3,420.00}}
\end{aligned}$$

**The total value of Stock B is $3,420.00.**

After we have determined the stock and total investment values, we will now determine each investment portfolio's weights. This is computed using the formula from step 4. Let us start by calculating the portfolio weight of Stock A. 

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Porfolio weight}&=\dfrac{\text{\$4,945.00}}{\text{\$8,365.00}}\\
&={\textbf{ 59.12\%}}
\end{aligned}$$

**The portfolio weight of Stock A is 59.12%.**

Finally, let us also compute the portfolio weight of Stock B. This is computed as follows: 

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Porfolio weight}&=\dfrac{\text{\$3,420.00}}{\text{\$8,365.00}}\\
&={\textbf{ 40.88\%}}
\end{aligned}$$

**The portfolio weight of Stock B is 40.88%.**
